entity.name: US employers added the fewest jobs in nearly a year in November
entity.description:
US employers added 210,000 jobs in November, the fewest in almost a year, The Associated Press reports. The unemployment rate fell from 4.6% to 4.2%, according to the Department of Labor, although this is still above the pre-pandemic jobless rate of 3.5%, according to The Associated Press.

More on the US jobs report:
- The number of jobs added this past month also show a sharp decline from October when the US economy added 546,000 jobs and came in well below Wall Street's November predictions of 573,000, CNBC and Marketwatch report.

- The Labor Department released figures on Thursday showing new claims for unemployment insurance rose last week but remain consistent with pre-pandemic levels

- Continuing claims for unemployment fell to 1.96 million, the lowest total since March 14, 2020 when the pandemic began

- Unemployment claims have been dropping steadily since September, giving economists signs the economy is showing strength, The Washington Post reports

entity.name: US employers added the fewest jobs in nearly a year in November
entity.description:
US employers added 210,000 jobs in November, the fewest in almost a year, The Associated Press reports. The unemployment rate fell from 4.6% to 4.2%, according to the Department of Labor, although this is still above the pre-pandemic jobless rate of 3.5%, according to The Associated Press.

More on the US jobs report:
- The number of jobs added this past month also show a sharp decline from October when the US economy added 546,000 jobs and came in well below Wall Street's November predictions of 573,000, CNBC and Marketwatch report.

- The Labor Department released figures on Thursday showing new claims for unemployment insurance rose last week but remain consistent with pre-pandemic levels

- Continuing claims for unemployment fell to 1.96 million, the lowest total since March 14, 2020 when the pandemic began

- Unemployment claims have been dropping steadily since September, giving economists signs the economy is showing strength, The Washington Post reports

entity.name: US employers added the fewest jobs in nearly a year in November
entity.description:
US employers added 210,000 jobs in November, the fewest in almost a year, The Associated Press reports. The unemployment rate fell from 4.6% to 4.2%, according to the Department of Labor, although this is still above the pre-pandemic jobless rate of 3.5%, according to The Associated Press.

More on the US jobs report:
- The number of jobs added this past month also show a sharp decline from October when the US economy added 546,000 jobs and came in well below Wall Street's November predictions of 573,000, CNBC and Marketwatch report.

- The Labor Department released figures on Thursday showing new claims for unemployment insurance rose last week but remain consistent with pre-pandemic levels

- Continuing claims for unemployment fell to 1.96 million, the lowest total since March 14, 2020 when the pandemic began

- Unemployment claims have been dropping steadily since September, giving economists signs the economy is showing strength, The Washington Post reports
